data.title: Trump administration seeks more federal police officers in Washington, DC
data.description:
By Courtney Rozen

U.S. President Donald Trump's administration has launched a website to recruit more law enforcement officers to police Washington, D.C., as it seeks to expand its control over the nation's capital.

The website advertises openings at Immigration and Customs Enforcement, the Drug Enforcement Administration and the U.S. Park Police. Hires will be stationed in Washington, D.C., for up to one year, according to the website.

The Trump administration launched the site to recruit "highly qualified and specifically trained individuals," said White House spokesperson Taylor Rogers.

Since June, the administration has deployed National Guard troops to various Democratic-led jurisdictions, including Los Angeles and Memphis as well as Washington, in an extraordinary expansion of the use of the military for domestic purposes. The deployments aimed to quell what Trump said were high levels of crime.

Trump this month declared victory over what he called a "crisis" of crime in Washington. A Reuters review of public safety records suggested that it was too early, however, to draw any sweeping conclusions about the effects of the deployments.

The new website links to the federal government's jobs board, which includes an advertisement for police officers to join the U.S. Park Police, the law enforcement arm of the National Park Service. Applications opened on September 29, according to the ad.

The Trump administration is looking for police officers to guard "National Park Service icons and symbols of democracy," the posting said, adding that officers will be required to maintain firearms proficiency. New hires may be eligible for a bonus of up to $70,000 over four years.

data.title: DYdX planning US market entry by 2026: Report
data.description:
Decentralized exchange dYdX is reportedly preparing to enter US markets by the end of 2025, its president Eddie Zhang said.

According to a Reuters report published Thursday, the company plans to enter the United States in the coming months, expanding its offerings to include spot trading on cryptocurrencies, such as Solana .

“It’s very important for us as a platform to have something available in the United States, because I think it represents, hopefully, the direction we’re trying to move in,” said Zhang, according to Reuters.

DYdX specializes in perpetual futures trading, a type of derivative that allows users to speculate on cryptocurrency prices without owning the underlying asset.

Zhang reportedly cited the increasingly favorable regulatory environment in the country under US President Donald Trump as part of the reason for the move, adding that he hoped agencies would provide guidance for perpetual contracts.

The Securities and Exchange Commission and Commodity Futures Trading Commission announced in September that they would consider bringing perpetual contracts onshore for US traders.

Planning governance vote over outage

On Monday, the decentralized exchange announced an open vote for users affected by operations pausing for about eight hours during a market crash in early October. The governance vote proposed compensating users with a total of $462,000 from the protocol’s insurance fund.

According to data from Nansen, the price of the protocol’s native token dYdX (DYDX) had fallen by about 50% in the last 30 days, from $0.60 to $0.30.

Cointelegraph reached out to dYdX for comment but had not received a response at the time of publication.

data.title: Arcosa, Inc. Announces Record Third Quarter 2025 Results
data.description:
Arcosa, Inc., a provider of infrastructure-related products and solutions, has reported its financial results for the third quarter ended September 30, 2025. The company has achieved record results, driven by significant revenue growth and improved profitability across all segments.

Financial Highlights

Arcosa reported a 27% increase in revenues, reaching $797.8 million compared to $640.4 million in the same period last year. The company's net income surged by 340% to $73.0 million, up from $16.6 million in the prior year. Adjusted EBITDA also saw a substantial increase of 53%, amounting to $174.2 million. The diluted EPS rose to $1.48 from $0.34, marking a 335% increase.

Business and Operational Highlights

The Construction Products segment experienced a 46% rise in revenues, reaching $387.5 million, primarily due to the acquisition of Stavola Holding Corporation. The Engineered Structures segment saw an 11% increase in revenues, driven by higher volumes and improved pricing in utility structures and wind towers. The Transportation Products segment reported a 22% increase in revenues, mainly due to higher tank barge deliveries.

Strategic Initiatives and Corporate Developments

Arcosa achieved its leverage goal two quarters ahead of schedule, reducing its net debt to adjusted EBITDA ratio to 2.4x. The company repaid $100 million of its acquisition term loan during the quarter. Additionally, Arcosa received new wind tower orders worth approximately $117 million, providing improved visibility for 2026 and 2027.

Management's Perspective

Antonio Carrillo, President and CEO, highlighted the success of the company's portfolio transformation, emphasizing the record results and strong cash conversion. He noted the significant contributions from the Stavola acquisition and the robust performance in the utility structures and wind towers businesses. Carrillo also mentioned the company's commitment to balance sheet strength and financial flexibility.

Future Outlook

Arcosa updated its full-year 2025 guidance, projecting consolidated revenues between $2.86 billion and $2.91 billion, and consolidated adjusted EBITDA between $575 million and $585 million. The company anticipates 32% growth in adjusted EBITDA for 2025, driven by strong contributions from Stavola and double-digit organic expansion.

Original SEC Filing: Arcosa, Inc. [ ACA ] - 8-K - Oct. 30, 2025

data.title: Annuity Sales Reach Another Record in Q3. The $100 Billion-Plus Quarters Keep Coming. — Barrons.com
data.description:
By Kenneth Corbin

Annuity sales have set another quarterly record, topping $100 billion for the eighth consecutive period, according to the industry trade group Limra.

In the third quarter, U.S. annuity sales checked in at $119.3 billion, up 4% from the same period a year ago. So far this year, Limra has tallied $345 billion in annuity sales, also a 4% annual increase.

"Despite continued market volatility, the equity market's overall performance attracted investors looking to counter persistent inflation, " says Bryan Hodgens, senior vice president and head of Limra research.

He says that the anticipated interest-rate cuts by the Federal Reserve will likely "dampen" sales of fixed annuities, but Limra is projecting total sales to top $450 billion for the year, which would mean yet another quarter of sales in excess of $100 billion.

By category, registered index-linked annuities, whose returns are correlated with the movement of a stock index, had a strong quarter, with sales checking in at $20.6 billion in the third quarter, up 20% from the same period in 2024. RILAs, which offer tax-deferred growth, have benefited from double-digit growth in equity markets this year and the easing of volatility in the third quarter, according to Keith Golembiewski, assistant vice president and director of annuity research at Limra.

"This is a perfect environment for RILAs, which offer protected growth with attractive caps and participation rates aligned with equity market returns," he says.

Fixed-index annuities, which are structured similarly to RILAs but offer more downside risk protection, saw sales of $33.2 billion in the third quarter, sliding 6% from last year.

Sales of traditional variable annuities checked in at $16.7 billion in the third quarter, up 11% from last year.

Fixed-rate deferred annuities were once again the most popular product category, posting third-quarter sales of $41.7 billion, up 3% from 2024. Those products have an interest rate that is set for a duration, after which the insurer can offer a new rate that is often subject to a minimum level. When the annuity reaches the withdrawal stage, investors receive regular payments from the insurer for a certain period or the rest of their lives.

Lower interest rates could weigh on demand for FRDs, but they typically offer better returns than CDs and "have become an attractive, short-term solution for [risk-averse] investors and their advisors looking for protected investment growth," Golembiewski says.

CME cattle futures take a pause after recent slides
data.description:
By Tom Polansek

Chicago Mercantile Exchange live cattle and feeder cattle futures took a breather on Thursday after falling hard recently on concerns over President Donald Trump's push to lower U.S. beef prices, traders said.

Ranchers continued to oppose Trump's plan to boost the country's imports of Argentine beef to reduce U.S. prices and they remained on edge about risks for the president to make further comments that could rattle the markets.

Already, speculative funds have liquidated long positions after Trump said in recent weeks that beef prices were too high, traders said.

CME December live cattle futures (LCZ25) rose 0.2 cent to close at 231.100 cents per pound, while November feeder cattle (FCX25) slipped 0.25 cent to end at 341.825 cents per pound.

The contracts rebounded on Wednesday after sliding earlier this week to their lowest levels since August 4.

U.S. cattle supplies remain low after ranchers reduced their herds because of a years-long drought that burned up pasture lands used for grazing and raised feeding costs.

Trump's administration further tightened U.S. supplies this year by blocking cattle imports from Mexico to keep out the flesh-eating parasite New World screwworm.

On Wednesday, Mexican Agriculture Minister Julio Berdegue said Mexico and the U.S. had not yet set a date to resume Mexican cattle exports.

It is necessary for Washington to keep its ban in place for now, said Bill Bullard, CEO of cattle producers' group R-CALF USA.

"Mexico first has to demonstrate that they've eliminated this pest from within their borders," he said.

In the hog market, CME December lean hog futures (LHZ25) edged up 0.05 cent at 80.825 cents per pound. The contract earlier hit its lowest level since July 30.

Declining cash prices have weighed on futures, a broker said.

Average hog weights in areas including Iowa, southern Minnesota and South Dakota rose to 291.2 pounds in the week that ended on October 25, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture. That was up from 290.1 pounds a week earlier and 286 pounds a year ago.

data.title: Western Digital 1Q Profit Soars as Data Center, AI Boost Sales
data.description:
By Paul Ziobro

Western Digital's quarterly profit more than doubled on the back of higher revenue, with results continuing to benefit from the growth of data centers and artificial intelligence.

The San Jose, Calif.-based data storage company on Thursday reported a profit of $1.18 billion, or $3.07 a share, for its fiscal first quarter ended Oct. 3, compared with $493 million, or 42 cents a share, in the same quarter a year earlier.

Adjusted earnings were $1.78 a share, exceeding the $1.59 a share expected by analysts polled by FactSet and the $1.69 a share the company forecast in July.

Revenue rose about 27% to $2.82 billion. Analysts projected $2.73 billion, while the company had forecast revenue up to $2.8 billion.

Chief Executive Irving Tan said the company is operating in a demand environment driven by growth of data storage in the cloud. He added that the AI boom is accelerating data creation, putting the company in good position to continue to capitalize.

For the current quarter, Western Digital forecast revenue between $2.8 billion and $3 billion and adjusted per share earnings between $1.73 and $2.03. Analysts were looking for revenue of $2.83 billion and adjusted per-share earnings of $1.74.

Chief Financial Officer Kris Sennesael said the outlook reflects continued revenue growth due to data center demand and improved profitability led by the adoption of its high-capacity drives.

Western Digital is also raising its quarterly cash dividend by 25% to 12.5 cents a share, reflecting confidence in its business momentum.

The new payout, equal to 50 cents a year, represents an annual yield of about 3.6% based on Thursday's closing price of $138.13. It will be paid on Dec. 18 to shareholders of record as of the close of business on Dec. 4.

Western Digital initiated a quarterly dividend in April at 10 cents a share.

The stock rose 12.3% in after-hours trading to $155.

Write to Paul Ziobro at paul.ziobro@wsj.com

The units were listed on the Nasdaq Global Market ("Nasdaq") and began trading under the ticker symbol "HAVAU" on October 23, 2025.
